개요: Jungmyeongjeon Hall, constructed in 1901, is a part of Gyeongungung which is today’s Deoksugung Palace, and it was used as the reception hall, banquet hall, and library. This was the place the banquet was held during the wedding ceremony of the Crown Prince (Sunjong) and Crown Princess Yun in 1907 and also the unfortunate place where the Japan-Korea Treaty of 1905 was concluded by force. It had been leased to foreigners in 1915 during Japanese colonial era and used as Seoul Club building.

Hwangudan Altar is the space where the emperor held memorial service for heaven. This is where Emperor Gwangmu of the Korean Empire which succeeded to the Joseon Empire held memorial service for heaven. Hwangudan Altar was completed in 1897 and was designed by Sim Eui-seok, the master builder for the imperial family at the time.

This is the renaissance style building designed by A. I. Sabatin of Russia in 1890 (Gojong 27). The main building was destroyed during the Korean War, and currently only the 3-story tower remains. This is famous for King Gojong’s refuge to avoid Japan’s pressure using force.
Chungdong First Methodist Church is a protestant church chapel, and construction of the church began in 1895 (Gojong 32) and was completed in October 1897 (Gwangmu 1).
도로명주소: Chungdong First Methodist Church, 46, Jeongdong-gil, Jung-gu, Seoul

명칭: Appenzeller Noble Memorial Museum (Former East Wing of Pai Chai School)
개요: This building was completed in 1916 and was used as a school building until Pai Chai middle and high schools moved to Gangdong-gu in 1984. Pai Chai School was established by the missionary Henry Gerhard Appenzeller in August 1885, and in the beginning, he purchased private houses in the area and used them as school buildings.

This place was previously occupied by Royal English Academy, German legation, and Gyeongseong District Court. After the liberation, the building was occupied by the Supreme Court of Korea and it reopened as Seoul Museum of Art from 2002.

It was completed in 1905 while restoring Gyeongungung Palace (Deoksugung Palace) which was burned in a huge fire. It was in charge of the modern education of the imperial family and aristocrats of the Korean Empire and today it is used as the office of the bishop of the Anglican Church of Korea.

명칭: Annex of Former Shina Daily News
개요: This is a 2-story reinforced concrete building with a basement constructed in the 1930's. The Korean branch of SINGER, an American company, initially used the building until Shina Daily News purchased the building in 1963. In 1975, Shina Daily News extended the building by adding 3rd and 4th floors and used it as the annex. Shina Daily News was incorporated into the Kyunghyang Shinmun during the merger of press by the new military regime in 1980.

명칭: Central Hall of the Korean Salvation Army
개요: Central Hall of the Korean Salvation Army was completed in 1928 to be used as the base for fostering Salvation Army officials and leading mission work and social services.

명칭: Seoul Cathedral of the Anglican Church of Korea
개요: The construction of Seoul Cathedral of the Anglican Church of Korea started in September 1922, and the first phase of the construction was completed in May 1926 and the second phase started in 1994 and was completed in 1996.
지정현황: Tangible Cultural Heritage of Seoul No. 35

명칭: Ewha Girls' High School Simpson Memorial Hall
개요: This is the school building of Ewha School completed in 1915. The cost of construction was covered by the donation provided by Miss Holbrook of Columbia River Brach, and the building was named ‘Simpson Memorial Hall’ to cherish the memory of Sarah Simpson, the sister of the donor who passed away at the time.

명칭: Ewha Girls' High School 100th Anniversary Memorial Hall
개요: This was the location of Sontag Hotel which was frequented by the ministers of various countries, missionaries, and pro-enlightenment people of Joseon in the 1890’s. Ewha Girls' High School Frey Hall was burned down in a fire in 1975 and the Ewha Girls’ High School 100th Anniversary Memorial Hall was constructed in the same spot.

명칭: Former National Assembly Building (Office of Seoul Metropolitan Council)
개요: This is a multipurpose building that Gyeongseongbu Office (currently, Seoul City Hall) constructed between 1933 and 1935 on the west side for the residents of Gyeongseong (citizens of Seoul). It served as the citizens’ hall at the time of construction, socializing place for US Army after the liberation, the National Theater, National Assembly building, and annex of Sejong Center for Performing Arts afterwards, and currently the office for Seoul Metropolitan Council.
Yi Yeong-hun was the composer of popular songs who was born in Seoul on March 6, 1960 and passed away on February 14, 2009.
도로명주소: Inside Deoksugung Palace Stonewall Walkway, 7, Jeong-dong, Jung-gu, Seoul

개요: Former Seoul City Hall is a renaissance style building originally constructed as an office of Gyeongseongbu in 1926. It is currently used as Seoul Library.

This was the Gyeongseong (Seoul) branch of Mitsui Trade of Japan completed in 1938 during Japanese colonial era. It was used as US Embassy and US Culture Center after liberation and Euljiro Annex of Seoul City Hall afterwards. In 2015, it opened as Grevin Museum exhibiting the wax figures of the world stars.

Jeongdong Theater was constructed in 1995 with the intention of restoring Wongaksa Theater, the first modern theater constructed in Korea. It is a complex performance theater which has been planning, developing, and presenting refined performances and arts and programs for citizens.

This is a small theater that opened in the annex of Seoul Cathedral of the Anglican Church of Korea in 1976. It held the first to the fifth Drama Festival of the Republic of Korea and was the center of the small theater movement which swept the country in the 1970’s.

이명칭: Yi Royal Family Museum, Yi Royal Museum
개요: This is the western hall of the Deoksugung National Museum of Art which was constructed in 1938 during Japanese colonial era to be used as an art museum. It reopened as a branch of National Museum of Contemporary Art in 1998 and has exhibited the old arts of Joseon, modern art, contemporary art, and the masterpieces of foreign masters.
This is the observatory located on the 13th floor of Seosomun Building I of Seoul City. It provides the view of the entire Deoksugung Palace, City Hall, Seoul Plaza, and Jeong-dong area at a glance.

This is the front gate of the Hanyang City Wall that surrounded the old capital of the Joseon Dynasty and the original name is Sungnyemun Gate. It was also called Namdaemun (South Gate) for it was located on the south side. Sungnyemun Gate was close to Hangang River which connects three southern provinces (Gyeongsang-do, Chungcheong-do, and Jeolla-do) and the markets developed inside and outside the gate during the late Joseon Period when commerce developed.
Sungjeongjeon Hall was the main hall of Gyeongheegung Palace constructed when Gyeongheegung Palace was constructed between 1617 (Gwanghaegun 9) and 1620 (Gwanghaegun 12).
지정현황: Tangible Cultural Heritage of Seoul No. 20

개요: This was the central beacon fire station which received beacon fire signals throughout the nation during the Joseon Dynasty period every day and reported to the Ministry of War. The station used torch at night and smoke during the day to make signals.

Namsangol Hanok Village was developed in 1998 in the 79,934m² (24,180 pyeong) site of Capital Defense Command in the north of Namsan Mountain with 5 Korean traditional mansions, Traditional Craft Museum, Cheonugak, traditional garden, Seoul Namsan Traditional Theater, and the New Millennium Time Capsule Plaza to embrace citizens and tourists. It gives a chance to have a variety of programs to experience Korean traditional culture and enjoy the beautiful scenery created by the hill, pavilions, and various flowers and plants in the heart of the busy city. The Millennium Time Capsule Plaza is located on the highest point of the traditional garden, and the memories of Seoul are placed in the time capsule in 1994 to commemorate the 600th anniversary of the establishment of Seoul as the capital city and will be opened 400 years later to commemorate the 1000th anniversary.
체험안내: Hanpung Cultural Experience, photograph shooting service, straw crafts demonstration, comments on traditional cultural heritage

개요: Time Capsule Plaza was constructed on November 29, 1994 to commemorate the 600th anniversary of the designation of Seoul as the capital city in 1394 (Taejon 3) by King Taejo who founded the Joseon Dynasty and 600 products of civilization that can represent Seoul at the time were placed in the time capsule and buried here.
도로명주소: Namsan Hanok Village, 28, Toegye-ro 34-gil, Jung-gu, Seoul

개요: Traditional Theater was built in the style of hanok that goes well with Namsangol Hanok Village and the basement floor has a projected stage that can present a variety of performances and the theater with 300 seats. The building is beautiful and it is a famous attraction frequented by both the citizens of Seoul and foreign tourists.

이명칭: Gyeongungung Palace, Temporary Palace at Jeongneung-dong, West Palace
개요: It was originally called Gyeongungung Palace but has been called Deoksugung Palace since 1907. Gates, pavilions and halls including Daehanmun Gate, Junghwamun Gate, Gwangmyeongmun Gate, Junghwajeong Hall, Junmyeongdang Hall, Seogeodang Hall, Seokjojeon Hall, Hamnyeongjeon Hall, and Jeukjodang Hall still remain in 61,500㎡ land.
이용시간:
Ticketing and Admission Time 09:00 ~ 20:00
 Closing Time 09:00 ~ 21:00
이용요금: Adult (25 or over) 1,000 wonAdult Group (10 or more) 800 won
체험안내: Try Korean Traditional Clothes, Changing of the Guards Ceremony

개요: Ahn Jung-geun Memorial Hall was established in 1970 with the donation from the people by the order of President Park Chung-hee in the site that was occupied by Joseon Shinto Shrine during Japanese colonial era. Martyr An Jung-geun was the independence fighter who assassinated Ito Hirobumi who was the first Japanese Governor-General of Korea.
휴무일: Mondays, January 1, Lunar New Year's Day, Chuseok

개요: Baekbeom Plaza was developed in Namsan Outdoor Theater Plaza in August 1968. Baekbeom Plaza was established to commemorate Kim Gu (penname: Baekbeom, 1876~1949) who became the Premier of the Provisional Government of the Republic of Korea.

Seokhojeong Pavilion is the archery field established in the late Joseon Dynasty period. It was the home of Korean archery and also the origin place for Korea’s Western archery team which dominates the world.

Namsan Cable Car is the first cable car installed in Korea. Namsan Cable car brings visitors from the platform near Myeong-dong to N Seoul Tower on the top of Namsan Mountain. On the cable car, visitors can take a look at the scenery of Namsan Mountain alongside the areas adjacent to the mountain such as Myeong-dong, Euljiro, and Chungmuro.

N Seoul Tower is Korea’s first tower attraction constructed in 1975. It is quite a tall tower reaching 480m in actual length, including the height of Namsan Mountain, 243m, and the height of N Seoul Tower, 236.7m. N Seoul Tower has the observatory that provides the view of Seoul at a glance, the Locks of Love terrace for couples to promise their eternal love and the revolving restaurant with the view of Seoul.

Myeongdong Cathedral is the cathedral of the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Seoul located in Myeong-dong, the birthplace of Korean Catholic church, and is the symbolic building of Korean Catholic Church. It was designed by Father Eugene Joan George Coste and was completed in 1898 and it was built by 1,000 or more volunteers.

Yi Hoe-yeong, born into a prestigious family in Jeo-dong, Jung-gu, Seoul in 1867 and he died for Korea in 1932 while fighting for independence. Korean government posthumously awarded him the Order of Merit for National Foundation, Independence Medal in 1962.
도로명주소: In front of YWCA Hall, 73, Myeongdong-gil, Jung-gu, Seoul

명칭: Main building of the Bank of Korea (Money Museum)
개요: The former main building of the Bank of Korea, constructed in 1912, is a renaissance style 2-story building with a basement. It was used as the central bank and opened as Money Museum in 2001.
휴무일: Mondays, Lunar New Year's Day Holidays and Chuseok Holidays, December 29~January 2 Following Year
장애인편의시설: Toilet and elevator for challenged people

명칭: Main branch of Shinsegae Department Store (Former Mitsukoshi Department Store)
개요: This was the Gyeongseong branch of Mitsukoshi Department constructed in 1930. It turned into Donghwa Department Store after Japanese colonial era, used as US Army’s post exchange store during the Korean War, and opened as Shinsegae Department Store in 1963.

명칭: Former main office of Korea First Bank
개요: The predecessor of former Korea First Bank was Joseon Savings Bank. The design for the building was selected through a contest for the first time in Korea, and the building was completed in 1935.
지정현황: Tangible Cultural Heritage of Seoul No. 71

개요: It started under the name of ‘Gyeongseong Branch of Incheon Post Office’ and was renamed ‘Gyeongseong Office’ in March 1901. The office had used the building newly constructed in October 1898, and a new 3-story building was constructed in front of this building in 1915, and the new building is today’s Seoul Central Post Office. Currently, the place is occupied by the post tower was newly constructed in 2007.

명칭: Museum of Sisters of St. Paul of Chartres
개요: Museum of Sisters of St. Paul of Chartres is a museum specializing in religion established to collect, study, preserve, and exhibit the history of Sisters of St. Paul of Chartres which started by four nuns dispatched to Korea and was established in Korean in 1888.

명칭: Global Village Folk Museum (Seoul Education Research & Information Institute)
개요: Global Village Folk Museum opened on February 16, 2006 and it exhibits the materials and relics related with the folklore culture around the world.
도로명주소: Seoul Education Research & Information Institute, 46, Sopa-ro, Jung-gu, Seoul

예약: Online and telephone reservation, and on-site purchase available
개요: Myeongchijwa (Meijiza) constructed in 1936, went through changes as it turned into Gukje Theater, Sigonggwan (municipal hall), and National Theater, and also was under threat of demolition. However, it reopened as Myeongdong Theater in 2009.

Nanta is Korea first non-verbal performance that premiered in October 1997 and won enthusiastic responses as much as it mobilized the largest audience in Korea. Nanta Theater opened in October 2009 and is where Nanta is performed all year round.
이용시간: Monday ~ Friday, Sunday and Holidays 17:00, 20:00 Saturday 14:00, 17:00, 20:00

개요: UNESCO House was completed in 1967 using the latest facilities at the time, and it was the first 13-story building in Korea and became the land of Myeong-dong.

Ginkgo tree of Hoehyeon-dong is a protected tree that is over 500 years. For it is old, it has a number of anecdotes. The most famous one is that 12 of the descendants of Jeong Gwang-pil became ministers.

Guksadang was the shrine that enshrined the guardian spirit called Mokmyeok Daewang from the early Joseon Dynasty to the late Joseon Dynasty to pray for the peace of the nation. The shrine was called the Mokmyeok Shrine previously, and it was relocated by force in 1925 during Japanese colonial era when Japanese people constructed Joseon Shinto Shrine in the place.

This is where Ryu Seong-ryong (Seoae) used to live. Ryu was appointed an official early in his life, and during Japanese Invasion of Korea in 1592, he became the Commander-in-Chief of Three Provinces governing Chungcheong-do, Jeolla-do, and Gyeongsang-do to manage military affairs.

명칭: Main office of Korean Red Cross
개요: Korean Red Cross, established in 1905, was incorporated into Japanese Red Cross in 1909 and became the Korean branch of Japanese Red Cross. However, it was reorganized into Korean Red Cross in 1949 following the liberation and has been involved in relief project, social service project, hospital, blood related project, and so on.

명칭: One and Only Resting Place in Myeong-dong, Myeong-dong Park
개요: Myeong-dong Park that opened in the 1950’s was the oasis of Myeong-dong which was crowded with commercial facilities. It was the playground for children in the neighborhood and a place to relax for workers from nearby shops and offices. It was also the place the heavy drunkards of Myeong-dong used to sober up before going home.

명칭: Artists who died young (Park In-hwan, Jeon Hye-rin, Yun Yong-ha, Yi Jung-seop, Kim Gwan-sik)
개요: Artists of Myeong-dong during the 1950's were passionately engaged in creative activities and left masterpieces. Some of them left this world too early after creating brilliant works.

명칭: A Day at Myeong-dong during the 1950's (Dong-a Daily Article in 1957)
개요: Myeong-dong during the 1950's was the place where people let out the desire of consumption that had been oppressed during Japanese colonial era and the Korean War. This is a presentation of a busy day at Myeong-dong in 1957 organized based on newspaper data. (Refer to the article 「A Day at Myeong-dong, Microcosm of Seoul」 of Dong-a Daily dated November 25, 1957)

명칭: Fashion and Trend of Myeong-dong' in the 1950~60's
개요: Korean women realized the discomfort of hanbok while undergoing the Korean War and began to prefer Western clothes. Boutiques selling clothes that suit the taste of women and beauty parlors began to open in Myeong-dong from the 1950’s

Tailor’s shops, boutiques, shoe stores, and beauty parlors opened in great numbers in Myeong-dong from the late 1950's and many schools and institutions teaching dress making and beauty art also opened centering on Myeong-dong. Boutiques at the time were the spaces that introduced new fashion to women.

명칭: Eunseong Jujeom, Myeong-dong Chanson - As Time Goes By (Park In-hwan)
개요: Eunseong Jujeom is the pub that actor Choi Bul-am’s mother ran and it was frequented by famous figures of the culture and art circles during the 1950’s ~ 1960’s. It was neater than other pubs and bars that it attracted all sorts of people.
도로명주소: In Front of ARITAUM, 59-7, Myeong-dong 1-ga, Jung-gu, Seoul

명칭: Story of Aseowon, Chinese Restaurant, and Chinatown
개요: Aseowon was the Chinese restaurant run by Chinese Korean people and it represented Chinese restaurants in the 1950’s ~ 1960’s and had been often used as the meeting place for famous politicians and business people. There is a Chinatown established during the time of enlightenment in the triangular block adjoining Namdaemun-ro at the western end of Myeong-dong from Noon Square to the rear alley of the Central Post Office. Old Chinese restaurants and stores carrying Chinese goods are here.
Namsan Arts Center started out as Drama Center in 1962 and turned into a modern theater through remodeling and reopened in June 2009.

명칭: The Society of the Holy Cross of the Anglican Church of Korea
개요: Society of the Holy Cross of the Anglican Church of Korea was officially established by Bishop Mark N. Trollope in September 14, 1925. The building was ruined during the Korean War and newly constructed by the Anglican Church of Korea in 1960.

Waryongmyo is the shrine dedicated to Zhuge Liang. It is not clear when it was constructed. However, it was burned down in a fire in 1924, reconstructed in 1934, and repaired to today’s condition in 1976.

It is standing in front of Canadian Embassy in Jeong-dong, Jung-gu, Seoul and is 17 m tall and 5.16m in circumference. It is currently over 500 years old and designated as the protected tree of Seoul in 1976.

Lotte Department Star Avenue, located in front of Lotte Department Store, exhibits photos showing Korean celebrities, media bronze plates showing hand prints of Korean Wave stars, cherished items of Korean celebrities, and Korean Wave contents using interactive system.

Shinhan Museum is Korea’s first museum specializing in financial history and it was established by Chohung Bank which was merged into today’ to help visitors have overall understanding of the history of finance in Korea.

Deoksugung Palace Stonewall Walkway starts from the stonewall on the left side of the Daehanmun Gate of Deoksugung Palace, continues along the alley between Deoksugung Palace and Habib House, and stretches up to Saemunan-ro 2-gil. It has been popular among lovers for a long time for the renaissance style modern building and great spots for dating.
This building was used as US Legation from 1883 to 1905. It was constructed in 1883 and extended four times to current condition.

명칭: Korea Electric Power Corporation (KEPCO) Building on Namdaemun-ro, Seoul
개요: This is a 5-story building with a basement floor constructed for Gyeongseong Electricity Co., Ltd in 1928, and the fire resistant and earthquake resistant design was applied to the building for the first time in Korea. 2 more floors were added after the liberation and currently it is occupied by Korea Electric Power Corporation Seoul HQ. For it has values for the history of modern architecture, it was designated as the Registered Cultural Heritage No. 1

A stone marker labeled, “Upside Down Statue”, in the site of the official residence of the Resident-General of Korea on August 22, 2015. This stone marker was prepared with 3 pieces of stone from the statue of Hayashi Gonsuke who took the initiative for the conclusion of the Japan-Korea Treaty of 1905.

This was used as the official residence of the Commissioner of the National Security Planning Agency from 1975 to 1990. It opened by the new name of the “Literature House Seoul“ in 2001 and it holds Special Lecture on Literature on Wednesdays, Literature Forum with Music, and Poem Recital every year.

The central point of Seoul is on top of Namsan Mountain and is located on 126 degrees 59 minutes 30 seconds east and 37 degrees 33 minutes 6 seconds north. The city installed a structure symbolizing the central point here in 2010.

Central Asia Village in Gwanghee-dong was developed initially by the people from Russia and Central Asia moving into the area after the establishment of diplomatic ties between Korean and Russia in the beginning of 1990’s.

Dongdaemun Fashion Town refers to all markets distributed on both sides of Heunginmun-ro and both sides of Cheonggyecheon-ro and the alleys near the road stretching up to 2 km from Gwangjang Market on Jongno 5-ga to Sinseol Market on Cheonggye 8-ga.
Dongdaemun Design Plaza is a mixed cultural space constructed in the former site of Dongdaemun Stadium. The construction began in April 2009 and the plaza opened in March 2014.

This is the water gate located in the south of Ogansumun Watergate which was located below Dongdaemun Gate of Hanyang City Wall. The stream that came down from Namsan Mountain joined the main stream of Cheonggyecheon Stream through the Igansumun Watergate outside the city wall. For it was made of two arched gates, it was called Igansumun (Two-Gate Watergate).

This memorial museum has the collection of records about a number of sports events and assemblies held in Dongdaemun Stadium and the inner facilities of the stadium which was constructed on May 24, 1925 and removed in December 2007 and related relics

This is a park on history and culture theme located in Jung-gu Seoul. This is a part of Dongdaemun Design Plaza developed in the site of Dongdaemun Stadium, and it exhibits the relics and architectural remains that were discovered during the construction of the plaza. It also shows the sports events that were held at Dongdaemun Stadium.

Sindang-dong Topokki Alley was established in the 1950’s. The spicy, salty, and sweet taste mainly made of hot pepper paste and black bean sauce is quite addictive, and the alley is one of the attractions in Seoul crowded with foreign visitors.

This was designed by Kim Jung-eop and was completed in 1965. It was used as a maternity hospital for over 30 years and today it is used as an ordinary office building. This building is characterized by exposed mass concrete and the smooth curves.

This bronze statue was erected to commemorate the achievement of martyr An Jung-geun, the Assistant Lieutenant General of Korean Righteous Army who assassinated Ito Hirobumi, the first Japanese Governor-General of Korea, at Harbin Station in Heilong Jiang, China. It was first located inside Soongeui Girls’ High School, moved in front of Namsan Park Management Office which was the site of Joseon Shinto Shrine in 1967, and a new bronze statue was prepared. In 2010, it was coated in gold paint to prevent the cracking on the statue.
도로명주소: Inside Namsan Park, 91, Sowol-ro, Jung-gu, Seoul

개요: Yi Si-yeong had enjoyed great wealth as the descendant of prestigious family, however, disposed of all his properties, and the six brothers including him joined the independence movement and defended the provisional government from beginning to end. He was elected as the first Vice President after liberation. This bronze statue was erected in Baekbeom Plaza on April 17, 1986 to cherish the patriotic spirit and devotion to the anti-Japanese national salvation movement and the establishment of democracy after liberation of the independence fighter, educator, and politician, Yi Si-yeong.
Kim Yu-sin (595~673) played a very important role for Silla to unify three states and also laid foundation for the Unified Silla Dynasty.
도로명주소: Inside Children's Plaza at Namsan Park, 39-2, Sowol-ro, Jung-gu, Seoul

개요: ‘Namsan Samsoon Stairs’ became famous after it appeared in the finale scene of the drama, <My Name is Kim Sam-soon>.
This city wall was constructed in 1396 (Taejo 5), and it surrounds Hanyang, the capital city of Joseon. Namsan (Mokmyeoksan) section stretches from the back alley of Jangchung Stadium to Namsan Park.

This was the place for holding memorial service to the soldiers and loyal subjects who were sacrificed in the line of duty during the Eulmi Incident in 1895, Imo Incident in 1882, and Gapsin Coup in 1884, however, was demoted to a park during Japanese colonial era. It turned into a neighborhood park in 1984 and was incorporated into a Namsan Park.

명칭: Meaning of Myeong-dong by Time and Location
개요: Japanese residents who lived on Jingogae hill during Japanese colonial era began to develop Myeong-dong for their needs. Myeong-dong grew into the center of finance, commerce, and culture after liberation.
Yi Bong-gu who became a journalist of The Maeil Shinmun in 1943 and later became a literary man active in Myeong-dong.

명칭: Tearoom Culture of Myeong-dong (1950~60's, Center of Culture and Arts)
개요: The tearooms in Myeong-dong had been the place for literary people and artists to discuss their work and take a rest from Japanese colonial era to liberation, the Korean War, and the 1960's.

명칭: History of Changes of Tearooms in Myeong-dong
개요: Tearooms opened for the first time during Japanese colonial era and developed into the place for combined arts and the base for literary people and artists during liberation and the Korean War. In 1970's, it became the central hangout for young people enjoying the hippie culture.

명칭: Myeong-dong, Center of Fashion and Trend in the 1970~80's
개요: Myeong-dong was notorious for the highest land price in Korean during the 1970's and the center for the latest fashion. Young people enjoyed the hippie culture from the West in tearooms and beer halls.

The National Theater was established in Sigonggwan (municipal hall) after the Korean War. Afterwards Myeong-dong becomes the center of performing arts. In the 1970's, however, the small theaters that began to open in Myeong-dong one by one after the National Theater moved led the performing arts. Typical theaters include Jayu Theater and Samilo Warehouse Theater.

명칭: Seoul Animation Center (Former Site of Japanese Residency-General of Korea)
개요: Seoul Animation Center was established in 1999 to support and foster Korean comics and animation industries.
This is a space for comics culture that opened in December 2013, and it is a 4-story building with 1 basement. It holds comics related exhibitions and programs and anyone can enjoy comics freely.
Namdaemun Market is the representative marketplace in Seoul with over 600 years of tradition and 10,000 or more stores in 58 buildings including the neighboring malls.

This was the previous location of the altar established in 1900 (Gwangmu 4) to cherish the memory of those who died in the line of duty during the Eulmi Incident in 1895, and it enshrined the tablets of the loyal subjects who died during Imo Incident in 1882 and Gapsin Coup in 1884.
Supyogyo Bridge was constructed in 1420 in the 2nd year in the reign of King Sejong, and it was an important bridge for it served as the water gauge to control flood.
지정현황: Tangible Cultural Heritage of Seoul No. 18

명칭: Monument of Korea Confucian Scholar's Independence Petition Sent to the Paris Peace Conference
개요: Monument of Korean Confucian Scholars' Independent Movement by Long Letter to Paris was constructed by the Association of Korean Confucian Scholars' Independent Movement by Long Letter to Paris in 1973 to commemorate the long letter sent by 137 representative Confucian scholars of Korea to petition the Paris Peace Conference held in Paris, France in 1919 for the independence of Joseon (Korea).

명칭: Statue of Patriotic Martyr Yi Jun
개요: Yi Jun who was dispatched as the emissary of Emperor to Hague Peace Conference held in Netherlands in 1907. However, he could not participate in the conference due to the interruption of Japan and England and the ignorance of the powers and died in Hague due to a disease he suffered there. This statue was constructed in Jangchungdan Park by Ilseonghoe Association in 1964 to cherish the lofty patriotism of the patriotic martyr Yi Jun.

명칭: Statue of Patriotic Martyr Yu Gwan-sun
개요: She is the independence fighter who joined the March First Independence Movement that was held during Japanese colonial era at the young age of 17. Her statue was originally erected on Taepyeong-ro (behind Namdaemun Gate) by Patriotic Martyr Statue Construction Association (Seoul Shinmun) in 1970 and moved to current location at the foot of Jangchung-dong in Namsan Park in 1971.
도로명주소: Inside Namsan Park, 101, Jangchungdan-ro, Jung-gu, Seoul

개요: March First Independence Movement Monument in Namsan Park was erected to commemorate the beginning of the nonviolent demonstration for independence following the proclamation of the independence of Korea on March 1, 1919 by Korean people who were under Japanese colonial rule. It was erected on March 1, 1999 on the 80th anniversary of the independence demonstration by the Independence Movement Monument Construction Association.

예약: Internet, mobile, telephone, and on-site reservation available
개요: This is the first National Theater established in Asia in 1950 in order to promote the development of national stage art. Current National Theater building was completed in 1973, and the National Theater currently has 3 organizations such as National Changgeuk Company of Korea, National Dance Company of Korea, and National Orchestra of Korea.
장애인편의시설: Group visit by challenged people, braille guidebook available

개요: Choe Hyeon-bae (penname: Oesol, 1894~1970) was a Korean linguist, activist, and educator who devoted his life to the study of Korean language such as establishing Korean grammar system.

Kim Yong-hwan made enormous efforts for the unification of Korean residents in Japan and the development of Federation of Korea Residents in Japan at the head of anticommunist activities. His statue was erected at the entrance of the National Theater in 1970 to cherish the memory of him who rendered great services in life time.
도로명주소: Entrance of National Theater, 59, Jangchungdan-ro, Jung-gu, Seoul

개요: Freedom Center designed by architect Kim Su-geun was completed in 1964 and used for anticommunist education. Freedom Center is known for applying the exposed mass concrete as it is for the first time in Korea.

Gwangheemun Gate is the Historical Site No. 10 and it is one of the four small gates of the city wall that surrounds the old capital, standing toward southeast. It was constructed in 1396 when Hanyang City Wall was constructed, and it was also called Sugumun Gate or Sigumun Gate.
